# Runtime discipline

Use for non-trivial changes to the **game application**: simulation loop, rendering, networking glue, workers, and dev tooling. Adapt paths to your repo.

## Architecture

- Clear ownership: who updates authoritative state, who runs the frame/tick loop, who presents visuals.
- Keep hot paths small; isolate debug and one-off logic.
- For async or worker boundaries, define message contracts and failure modes up front.

## Rendering

- Keep draw/submit paths intentional; avoid implicit global order where it causes bugs.
- If you use GPU APIs, lifecycle shaders/materials consistently (create, warm up, dispose).

## Concurrency

- Do not block the UI thread on worker round-trips without feedback to the player.
- Treat transferred buffers as consumed; copy when buffers must be reused.

## Tooling

- If you use hot reload, follow one established registration pattern — no duplicate singletons on refresh.

## Diagnostics

- Prefer centralized debug toggles over scattered flags in hot loops.
